@node 08019.009
Subject: Re: Mesa3.1
From: Sam Jordan <sam_jordan@spin.ch>
Date: Thu, 16 Dec 1999 19:15:15 +0200

Am 16-Dez-99 schrieb Sealey, M.:

>How hard would it be to integrate Mesa3.1 sources
>into the StormMESA ones?

>I feel like a challenge ;)

>Bear in mind that I 

>a) Only have an 030
>b) .. therefore can't test it ;)

>I just feel like doing something useful ;)

Integrating Mesa3.1 into the current StormMesa software is quite futile.
Mesa upgrades were always very difficult even for me, it's a much
bigger work as you might expect. The shared library stuff is also a
very complicated thing, it's actually impossible to build the
StormMesa shared libraries using standard operation procedures,
quite some tricks and hacks are needed to achieve the right results.
Furthermore I don't see StormMesa as a really clean software, there
is lot of messy stuff in there, especially the AOS interface.

Therefore it is my opinion that it's no good idea to integrate 3.1
into StormMesa. It's much better to port Mesa 3.1 from scratch, but
by trying to migrate all the good AMIGA-specific code to the new
port. Additionally the overall design of Mesa for AMIGA must be
completely rethought, a new AOS interface must be designed and
developed.

If anyone really wants to work on such a new Mesa version it is
important to know, that this is not a simple small project which
is quickly done, but it's a larger one, if the result is supposed
to become something really usable.

Now let me say, that I really won't have any time to work on Mesa
for long, because I have plenty of other important things to do.
Therefore it would be very fine, if someone would continue Mesa
development with the StormMesa-philosophy in mind, which means to
provide a GL implementation especially suitable for High-End
equipment with support of PowerPC and 3D hardware technology.

But I would not at all recommend to take over the StormMesa archive
and take it as reference. There are better ways to proceed:

a) Re-port Mesa 3.1 until it works (even without support of all
those new technologies) and afterwards try to migrate all the
usable code from StormMesa. This certainly requires that the people
working on it have quite deep knowledge both with PowerPC programming
and Warp3D programming.

b) Get in contact with the authors of the other Mesa ports and try
to make a new 'AmigaMesa' software out of all those Mesa versions
for AMIGA which exist. The advantage would be that those authors
might be able to contribute a lot to the project, so that results
would be available quite soon, provided that the authors have some
interest to work on such an implementation. A well-designed and
well-implemented AmigaMesa version would fit very nicely into
future AOS releases.

All persons which eventually would like to work on such a project,
just tell me, I will link you all together. I will also accompany
the project and try to give as much useful input as possible, and
finally I'm very interested to do the integration of the new
Mesa implementation into future OS releases.

Important is to recognize that such a project doesn't automatically
give good results, it's actually quite a challenge to set up
such a project. There must be at least one people with the ability
to lead such a project, to do all the organization and to push
the project forwards. Otherwise there is the risk, that the project
approaches a stagnation phase where no real progress is made anymore.

bye
