Hi,

First of all, please do not misinterpret this mail, I don't want to
critizize anybody, nor do I want to put myself in charge or anything else=
,
I just want to give some advice.

Sam's suggestion to have an organized Quake porting group is a great idea.
The basic intention should be to have a feature-packed Quake version, not
multiple ports of Quake where some have this feature, and others have
this. So, I would suggest some careful planning is needed.

First of all, I would suggest getting a CVS server somewhere on the net.
IIRC, ninemoons.com offer this for open source projects, or COSA. For a
project with many people working on it, it is absolutely necessary to hav=
e
a CVS. You'll be faced with the task of maintaining a port that's suppose=
d
to be bukld in many different ways, you'll have a WarpUp version, an=20
OpenGL version, different flavors of software renderers, even a 68k
version with hardware accleration and a PowerUp version should be
considered. A CVS repository offers support for this, as well as
maintaining stable branches and different versions. Source repositories
just maintained on a CVS server tend to get diff-orgys, which can lead to
all kinds of problems later...

The next step would be to assemble a fixed team before anybody does any
real work to do the different stuff. Even if Quake isn't hard to port at
first glance, you still have to coordinate the effort, to avoid people
doing the same work twice, and to avoid putting in features that may
hinder other features. For instance, consider the way the input is done:
If it's messed up, it will be hard to put in support for analog joysticks=
,
sega pads, or playstation pads.

What also may be an issue is the compiler: Steffen already suggested
StormC, but this should be agreed on by everybody in the team (some peopl=
e
may not have StormC at all), plus it may be an issue for PowerUp versions=
.=20
Doing the port with differnet compilers may clutter the code with unneede
#ifdefs, if it's necessary to use different compilers, pack up the
differences in different header files.

Of course, the whole issue is about the fun of porting it, but there
should be a team leader that everybody agrees on, and he must be in
charge, more or less directing the team.=20

Ok, please understand that this may sound a bit like I want to take charg=
e
of this, but it's not the case, I just want to help out. This is just fro=
m
my experience. For example, it took about 4 hours to have Abuse running o=
n
an Amiga, sound, input, display and all, but afterwards, it took about
three weeks to get it to work smoothly (even though I have been accused o=
f
being an idiot because Abuse was way to slow on an A500...).

Make this a great project, this will avoid the chaos that came with Doom
(how many version where there ? 6 ?), and the Quake port will be the most
feature packed version of all platforms.=20

Me or Hans-J=F6rg will probably volunteer to take over the OpenGL part on=
ce
the MiniGL is finished...

