Hi,

On Thu, 30 Dec 1999, Alan Lee Maurice Buxey wrote:
> > It's really hard to say. Based from what I've learned from Heretic II, I'd
> > say that the major problem is the fillrate of the Permedia2 chip. Even in
> > 640x480, the chip is pushed to the limit but the overdraw that any Quake
> 
> can you define 'limit' - as my Perm2 can do 800x600x16 at 35 fps with OpenGL
> gfx - thats fine and all i need in a game ;-)

That's mostly untextured, or not filling the whole screen. The way Quake
and Quake 2 are laid out, they overdraw quite a lot. This means, that
sometimes, the screen is overdraw 4 to 5 times. Even though a lot of work
is dropped by the zbuffer, it's still a very limiting factor. So, the
Permedia may be able to fill the whole screen at 800x600 in 35 fps once,
but not twice, or even more. Plus Quake and Heretic 2 use two-pass
lightmapping, so even if the engine would be optimal and drawing only the
things really visible, every polygon is drawn twice.

> > I would expect that it could theoretically be played in 800x600, although
> > there are other limiting factors, like the video memory required: 800x600
> > = 480000 pixels, three buffers plus Z buffer makes about four megabytes
> > for the display alone, plus a workbench screen, plus textures, plus
> > lightmaps, plus skins...
> 
> luckily, then , that we have 8Mb cards ;-)

Yes, but even now, these 8 MB are cramped full. A "normal" level uses up
to 15 MB of textures, so the 4 MB of free memory on the board are already
filled by the demo levels. Fortunately, caching does a lot of sense
here... :)

